<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43496883" data-cid="43496883">
    <div id="comment_43496883">
        <header data-points="0" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="You need to read up on UK justice."><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>You need to read up on UK justice.<span> (0)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><span class="author" title="author name and user ID">Anonymous Coward</span> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3666873&cid=43496883">(#43496883)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43496883" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="0" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>The extradition rulings were SOLELY about whether the extradition order was correctly completed. NOTHING ELSE.</p><p>1) It was signed by the prosecutor and not a judge as was intended, but it was accepted anyway.<br>2) The claims by **by the prosecutor** were claims that allowed extradition, but nothing about whether the claims were valid was addressed (this is why it was intended to be done by a judge not the prosecutor: judges judge the criminal culpability, prosecutors just make claims).</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_43496883">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="3666873" data-cid="43496883">
