        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="false equivalence altert"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>false equivalence altert<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~globaljustin" class="author" title="author name and user ID">globaljustin (574257) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3666873&cid=43496243">(#43496243)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43496243" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><blockquote><div><p>They don't have to be expert engineers</p></div></blockquote><p>They **do** have to have a working knowledge of the product of the company.</p><p>You're giving Eric Schmidt a pass...he doesn't deserve it. He should have a grasp of these concepts enough to make decisions about resource allocation. That means a systemic-level understanding, not all details.</p><p>We need to demand CEO's have core competency...weird as it is to say that, it's true. "management" is only part of the picture of leading a company.</p></div>
