    <div id="comment_43496521">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:false equivalence altert"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:false equivalence altert<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~retchdog" class="author" title="author name and user ID">retchdog (1319261) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3666873&cid=43496521">(#43496521)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43496521" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>First, google isn't in the anonymizing-proxy business.</p><p>Second, this is for an interview. In order to get the subject to explain things, it's often a good move to play yourself down, give a terse summary, and let the subject elaborate on things.</p><p>Third, depending on what he meant by "the recipient needs to be replicated," i'd say he gets the gist of the tor network. There <i>are</i> multiple recipients in the routing chain. "Replicated'' isn't the best word to use, but it's not completely wrong.</p></div>
