<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43495357" data-cid="43495357">
    <div id="comment_43495357">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:"Immeasurable Impact"??"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:"Immeasurable Impact"??<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~MatrixCubed" class="author" title="author name and user ID">MatrixCubed (583402) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3666873&cid=43495357">(#43495357)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43495357" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>"Immeasurable impact on issues surrounding technology". Not "inventions".</p><p>As a "good guy", Google's contribution to any part of many peoples lifestyles with regard to the technology used is indisputable. (Google search &gt; competition, Android market share &gt; competition, Chrome performance and stability &gt; competition, NaCL, Play store, etc etc. They're not perfect, but they are certainly usable and viable, and often better, alternatives to their competitors.)</p><p>As a "bad guy", Google's stereotypical credo of "do no evil", after they've gained such weight in the technology world, is coming into question (most recently? see CISPA).</p><p>Together, these certainly form a kind of impact, and given Google's ubiquity in a lot of peoples' lives, an immeasurable one.</p></div>
